  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Vitamin D has become important for periodontal disease due to play a role in autoimmunity,
      bone mineral metabolism and inflammation. Our aim was to investigate the relation between
      serum 25-hydroxy vitamin D levels, clinical periodontal parameters and blood serum
      biomarkers. The subjects were evaluated in 2 groups as chronic periodontitis (n= 30) and
      periodontally healthy subjects (n= 30). Periodontal parameters and fasting venous blood
      samples were taken from the subjects to assess each patient's periodontal status and for
      biochemical analyses (25-hydroxy vitamin D (25-OH vit D), osteoprotegerin (OPG), receptor
      activator of nuclear kappa B ligand (RANKL), C-telopeptide (CTx), tumor necrosis factor-α
      (TNF-α)).
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
